description: Cristiani Hugenii Zulichemii, Const. f. Systema Saturnium.

In 1656, Christiaan Huygens came very close to solving a mystery about Saturns rings. Because of the way that Saturn rotates on its axis, the rings do not always appear as a complete circle. Since the rings do not always appear as a complete circle, people wondered, Are there really rings around Saturn? This image is Christiaan Huygens depiction of the changing appearance of Saturn and its rings. Using a state of the art telescope from that era, Huygens declared that Saturn had a solid ring that was extremely flat and disconnected from the surface of the planet. He was nearly correct! Today, we know that Saturn has multiple rings made of mostly ice. Saturn's ring system extends far beyond the planet and is so wide that 22 planet Earths could fit across them. Yet, in its thinnest places, the rings are only as tall as a three-story building. Saturn is so far away that it would take six years to get there by space travel; but despite how far away it is from us here on Earth, we can still see parts of its rings from our own planet.

description: Text from negative sleeve: Burnham, Roger Noble. Sculptor. 4 negs.

Sculptor Roger Burnham Noble and an unidentified man holding a relief panel with 3 classicizing nude dancing figures. Behind them is another relief panel with a man with shackles on his wrists facing a man holding a lightning bolt and an oil lamp and with the planet saturn and smoke stacks behind them.
Access to this collection is generously supported by Arcadia funds.

Description: The SIVB (Third stage [IVB] of Saturn Launch vehicle) stage after Lunar Module (LM) ejection. On command from the Mission Control Center in Houston, the spent SIVB (Third stage [IVB] of Saturn Launch vehicle) maneuvered away from the hard-docked Command Service Module (CSM) and Lunar Module (LM). The SIVB (Third stage [IVB] of Saturn Launch vehicle) continued along the modified trajectory to impact on lunar surface. Part of the Lunar Module (LM), including three of the four thrusters in a reaction control system thruster quad, can be seen along the bottom edge of the frame. Original film magazine was labeled NN,filmtype was SO-368 (Color Exterior),80mm lens.

description: The beauty of the heavens : a pictorial display of the astronomical phenomena of the universe : one hundred and four coloured scenes, illustrating a familiar lecture on astronomy

If we had to guess, wed say youre reading this from somewhere on planet Earth. The ancient Greeks used the word planet, which means wanderer, to describe the huge objects they saw in the sky because they appear to move while the stars in the background appear to stand still. While now we know that everything is moving, including the stars, the name planet stuck with us. According to how scientists define the term, there are eight planets in oursolar system, meaning, objects that orbitthe Sun. The sun uses gravity to keep the planets spinning in orbit, and it also provides heat and light to each of them. The four inner planets are Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars. Composed of mostly rock and metal and with solid surfaces, these are given the term terrestiral or Earth-like. The four outer planets are Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. They are all much larger than the inner planets; Jupiter is larger than the seven other planets combined! In addition to their size, they also differ from the inner planets in that they have no solid surfaces; they are made of liquid and gases, and they each have a ring system and several moons. Not such a small world, after all.

description: On black ground, a male figure viewed from the mid-torso, rendered in white hatching lines; his head shown in profile at left and right to suggest movement, his left arm rendered in four positions with curving lines to indicate motion. Surrounding the left eye of the frontal face, a square shows a small section of the man's face in full color. Behind the figure, horizontal yellow, red, and blue lines recede to the horizon. Dotted white lines emerge from the man's eyes, the ones at center pointing up towards an array of colorful graphics. At top, printed white text: UNDERSTANDING TAXES '79; below, a curving group of images including the American flag; a portrait of Abraham Lincoln; the planet Saturn; a portrait of Franklin Delano Roosevelt; a hand holding a Social Security card; a silver dollar coin, a purple hot-air balloon with the yellow label "W-2"; the central oval medallion of a one-dollar bill, the number"1" inside; a purple rose; a hand holding a card printed with "APRIL 15" in black block letters; a white line drawing similar to a plug or nuclear radiation symbol, and a white dove carrying a sheet with "1040-A" printed in orange in its beak. Below these icons, a curving row of purple question marks. Centered below, the earth printed in turquoise. Composition contained within white framing line.
